<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / Anger as Ulster bags bulk of EC grant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR MPs last night accused the prime minister of using the European
Community regional aid package to buy Ulster Unionist votes on the
Maastricht treaty. The attack followed the government's announcement that
Northern Ireland will receive more than half of the nearly Pounds 2bn-worth
of EC funding allotted to help the UK's poorest regions over the next five
years.
Mr Tim Sainsbury, the industry minister, said in a Commons written answer
yesterday that the province would receive Pounds 1.04bn, with Pounds 690m
going to Merseyside and Pounds 260m to the Highlands and Islands.
EC ministers last week decided how to apportion the Community's structural
funds between the 12 member states. The UK receives funds for Northern
Ireland, Merseyside and the Highlands and Islands because the regional gross
domestic product of these regions is 75 per cent or less of the EC average.
The government has divided the Pounds 2bn according to population.
Mr George Howarth, MP for Knowsley North, was among Merseyside Labour MPs to
attack the decision. He said: 'We did expect Pounds 1bn on Merseyside. It
would appear that Mr Major is willing to pay an extremely large price for
the nine Ulster Unionist votes last week.'
</TEXT>
