<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / When efficiency is not enough: Problems faced by Nuclear
Electric as it aims for privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YESTERDAY was Nuclear Electric's chance to shine before the government's
review of nuclear power is launched later this year. Armed with impressive
statistics on market share and job reductions, it put up a creditable
performance.
Nonetheless the company has an uphill, perhaps impossible, task in achieving
the targets it has set for itself.
In the coming review Nuclear Electric and Scottish Nuclear, its counterpart
north of the border, will be attempting to demonstrate that the City was
wrong. Not only is the industry a commercial success, it is capable of
thriving in the private sector without subsidy, they will argue.
The country should also invest further in the sector by commissioning the
pressurised water nuclear reactor, Sizewell C, to enable it to start
producing electricity from the middle of the next decade.
If decisions about the nuclear industry were based on improving efficiency
alone, Nuclear Electric and Scottish Nuclear would stand every chance of
winning their arguments. In the past three years, Nuclear Electric has
improved productivity from 2.9GW to 4.5GW per hour and return on capital is
up from 4.5 per cent to 10.1 per cent.
Figures like these enabled Mr John Collier, Nuclear Electric chairman, to
reiterate yesterday his assurances that the company will make an operating
profit in 1995-96 even before taking account of the nuclear levy which is
charged to every electricity consumer to pay for the decommissioning of
plants inherited by Nuclear Electric.
In addition the company says the levy will not be needed at all beyond 1998.
Environmental groups including Friends of the Earth are not convinced. More
important for the future of privatisation, neither is the City. Fears over
the costs of future waste management and decommissioning lay behind the
aborted privatisation of the nuclear industry in 1989.
Yesterday's accounts showed that accumulated provisions for nuclear waste
and liabilities are Pounds 10.46bn, against Pounds 9.88bn in the previous
year. A critical factor in these figures is Nuclear Electric's assumptions
that decommissioning will take place over 100 years, which it wants
increased to 135. But environmentalists say, and the City fears, that both
timescales will have to be revised downwards, dramatically increasing the
cost.
Further uncertainties are raised by Nuclear Electric's negotiations with
British Nuclear Fuels for fuel services which amount to more than a third of
Nuclear Electric's costs. The deal is having to be revised following the
government's refusal to underwrite the risks of costs rising.
Mr Collier said yesterday he would like the government to take over the
liabilities the company has inherited from the Central Electricity
Generating Board and the levy that goes with it.
This would enable Nuclear Electric to widen its appeal to potential
investors since liabilities from pressurised water reactors are lower and,
arguably, easier to predict than from the ageing magnox reactors inherited
from the CEGB.
The government last winter declined to do this. It seems unlikely to change
its mind.
The nuclear industry's best hope in the forthcoming review is that the
government will set wide terms of reference which compare the environmental
impact of all forms of energy for making electricity, including their
emissions of carbon and sulphur.
The signs from Whitehall are that the review will only ask whether the
private sector is prepared to fund the building of Sizewell C. The key to
that, and to the privatisation of Nuclear Electric, will be the attitude of
the government on underwriting decommissioning and waste disposal costs.
</TEXT>
