<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / Powerbroker who fell from grace: Obituary - T. Dan Smith
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
T. DAN SMITH, the charismatic Geordie local politician who fell from grace
in the Poulson corruption scandal, died yesterday in the Freeman Hospital,
Newcastle, aged 78. He was undergoing surgery after collapsing at home.
One of Britain's most ebullient post-war local government figures, the
miner's son rose from a boyhood and socialist youth in the modest terraced
streets of Wallsend to become a tireless powerbroker, driven by a mission to
change his native north-east and, say his enemies, to wield power.
For good or ill, he stamped his vision on Newcastle upon Tyne, where he was
council leader for five years in the 1960s, sweeping away slums and ushering
in the city's 'Brasilia' era of multi-storey blocks of flats and motor-ways.
One city alone seemed insufficient for the energies of the man who became
known as Mr Newcastle; he became the first chairman of the northern Economic
Planning Council, formulating a vision of change for the entire region; a
member of the Royal Commission on Local Government in England; and chairman
of Peterlee new town development corporation on County Durham.
His political career was wrecked by his involvement in the web of corruption
surrounding the architect John Poulson. In 1974, T. Dan Smith was sentenced
to six years in prison for accepting Pounds 156,000 from Mr Poulson.
Released after three years, Mr Smith was politically persona non grata; only
in 1987 did his local Labour party agree to his being readmitted.
He remained a forceful personality, campaigning after his release for
prisoners' rights. He also relished a new role as an independent,
challenging pundit on north-east matters; only a few days ago he was taking
part, with his usual verve, in a Radio Newcastle phone-in.
</TEXT>
