<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / SIB probes Goldman Sachs deal: Maxwell shares transaction
may be subject to British regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SECURITIES and Investments Board has launched an inquiry into a
transaction between Goldman Sachs, the US-based investment bank, and one of
the pension schemes formerly controlled by the late Robert Maxwell.
The Securities and Futures Authority, the self-regulatory body which
oversees Goldman Sachs' UK operations, has already examined the transaction
and did not consider disciplinary action because the transaction had been
booked through Goldman Sachs in New York, and was therefore outside the
jurisdiction of UK regulators.
Instead, the authority passed information to the US Securities Exchange
Commission.
But in a letter to the Commons social security committee, released
yesterday, SIB said it had 'come across a point which it does believe merits
further UK inquiry'.
It is believed that SIB has learned that the transaction was cleared and
settled in London, which could make it subject to UK regulatory rules.
If SIB decides UK regulators do have jurisdiction over the transaction and
Goldman Sachs is found to have breached UK securities rules, SIB could order
it to pay Pounds 56m to two pension schemes. It could also levy a fine.
In June Goldman Sachs was fined Pounds 160,000 for three breaches of rules
in connection with transactions between it and the Maxwell interests.
The inquiry relates to a transfer in April 1991 of 12.5m shares in Maxwell
Communication Corporation from the MCC Works Pension Scheme to two Swiss
trusts established by Robert Maxwell.
Goldman Sachs acted as agent in the transfer on the orders of Mr Kevin
Maxwell. He ordered payment for the shares to go not to the pension schemes
but to Bishopsgate Investment Trust, a company which acted for the Maxwell
family private interests.
Responding to SIB's letter, Goldman Sachs said: 'As we understand it, the
SIB is examining a specific jurisdictional point. We have fully responded to
their inquiry of today. As has been true in the case of other regulatory
authorities which have examined these trades, we would expect to respond
appropriately to any further inquiries the SIB may make.'
While SIB's letter refers to the MCC works scheme, the transaction was part
of a larger deal in which shares were purchased from the Mirror Group
Newspaper pension scheme and the proceeds were also directed to Bishopsgate.
</TEXT>
