<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / N Cyprus may end protection of Nadir
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS, RACHEL JOHNSON and JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NORTHERN CYPRUS has given its strongest indication to date that it may be
prepared to abandon its uncompromising protection of Mr Asil Nadir, the
fugitive former Polly Peck chairman.
The authorities, with the apparent blessing of the Turkish government, have
invited senior officers of the Serious Fraud Office to the island without
any apparent diplomatic strings.
The fraud office had argued that it was unable to pursue its investigation
on the island because the local authorities and Ankara were insisting on a
formal diplomatic exchange.
This would have implied British recognition of Turkish sovereignty over
northern Cyprus, which the UK refuses to give.
The Serious Fraud Office confirmed last night that one of its investigating
teams travelled to northern Cyprus yesterday at the 'invitation' of the
Turkish Cypriot authorities.
'We have been invited to explore the possibility of future investigation and
co-operation,' the fraud office said last night.
It is believed that a two-person team, led by Ms Lorna Harris, the SFO
lawyer handling the Nadir case, is representing the Serious Fraud Office on
the island.
The Foreign Office said last night that there was no diplomatic coercion
behind the decision and that the invitation had come from the Turkish
Cypriots.
The initiative follows a visit to Turkey last month by Ms Harris at which
she is understood to have discussed how Mr Nadir might be persuaded to
return to the UK to attend his trial in September.
The visit was the first apparent break in the deadlock over attempts to
bring Mr Nadir to justice since he jumped his Pounds 3.5m bail on May 5th.
and flew to northern Cyprus.
Mr Nadir has indicated his intention to fly to Turkey to regain the remnants
of his former business empire which he would be legally able to own and run
in Turkey although he is a bankrupt in the UK.
There was no immediate reaction yesterday from the northern Cypriot
authorities or from Mr Nadir to the development. However SFO officials
indicated they hoped the invitation signified the prospect of significant
progress on the Nadir case in the coming days.
</TEXT>
