<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / Waste mountains prove difficult to conquer: The lesson of a
German recycling scheme that came to grief through overspill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE spectre over the government's new packaging recycling moves, announced
yesterday, is a similar German scheme launched two years ago.
Mr John Elkington, director of Sustainability, an independent environmental
consultancy, said yesterday: 'A few years ago I would have welcomed this
move wholeheartedly. In the wake of the (German) experience I am concerned
that the simple setting of ambitious targets is only a small part of what
needs to be done.'
The crisis in the German waste recycling scheme, the Duales System
Deutschland (DSD), came to a head last month when it tottered on the edge of
bankruptcy before being propped up at the last minute by funds from
industry.
Even so, a mountain of waste - particularly plastics - is still threatening
to overwhelm German towns. The country's recycling capacity has not kept
pace with people's taste for filling the scheme's yellow sacks with
carefully sorted rubbish, while demand for recycled material has been much
less than expected.
The effects are spilling over into other countries. Mr Cameron Mclatchie,
chairman of British Polythene Industries, one of Europe's leading makers of
polythene film, said that this year the price of imported black film to
cover silages had dropped 'through the floor' to around Pounds 60 per tonne
 -about half the cost to him of collecting it from British farms for
recycling.
Ms Jane Bickerstaffe, technical director of the Industry Council for
Packaging and the Environment (INCPEN), said: 'Several recycling firms have
gone out of business in this country in the past six months because German
waste is offered here.' Without those 'repercussions' from Germany, the
packaging industry 'could certainly achieve 50 per cent recycling by the
year 2000', she said.
Mr Peter Hindle, an associate director of environmental at Procter &amp; Gamble,
also warns that the costs can be high. P&amp;G's use of recycled plastic for
detergent bottles 'currently does add to costs', and was no longer a clear
competitive advantage as 'everyone's doing it'. Consumers were now
interested in refillable bottles and other measures that reduced the amount
of packaging, he added.
Some industrialists and environmental consultants have also questioned
whether the proposals could, ironically, be damaging to the environment
because of the extra transport needed to collect the rubbish, and the energy
used in washing and recycling it into usable material.
Mr Mclatchie said that, when it comes to household waste, 'after you wash it
and transport it, the cost of getting it back in environmental terms is
greater than any benefit. And do you actually see the British consumer
washing up used frozen pea bags?'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4953 Refuse Systems.
    P2671 Paper Coated and Laminated, Packaging.
</IN>
<XX>
