<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / Bundesbank may cut interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GERMAN interest rates could be cut further this week even though inflation
has increased again, economists in Germany argued yesterday, writes
Christopher Parkes. The cost of living in western Germany rose at an annual
rate of 4.3 per cent in the month to mid-July, compared with 4.2 per cent in
June, the federal statistics office reported.
Mr Martin Hufner, chief economist at Bayerische Vereinsbank, noted that in
the previous three months prices had risen at a 'moderate' annual rate of
3.1 per cent, thanks partly to cheaper oil. Though money supply growth still
exceeded the Bundesbank's target range, the rate of expansion was weakening.
Mr Hufner said renewed tension in the European monetary system was an
important argument for a rate cut at the central bank's meeting tomorrow,
the last before the summer break.
The Bundesbank announced yesterday it would accept variable bids from
commercial banks for short-term funds in its weekly money market operation.
Some dealers believe the cost of borrowing short-term funds should come down
today by about 0.15 percentage points to 7 per cent.
The Spanish peseta, Portuguese escudo and Danish krone came under some
selling pressure yesterday afternoon. The French franc weakened slightly
against the D-Mark.
</TEXT>
