<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 93 / IBM takes Dollars 8.9bn charge and cuts 60,000 more jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON, LOUISE KEHOE and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Business Machines, the struggling US computer maker, is to
slash a further 60,000 jobs worldwide by the end of 1994 - on top of 25,000
already cut this year - and sharply reduce its manufacturing capacity and
office space.
The group yesterday took an Dollars 8.9bn (Pounds 5.93bn) pre-tax charge in
its second-quarter results to cover the upheaval.
Yesterday's action, which included a 54 per cent cut in the quarterly
dividend, is the first major restructuring by Mr Lou Gerstner, who joined
IBM as chairman last April with a mandate for radical change.
Underscoring the problems facing him, IBM also announced that it suffered a
second quarter net loss before special charges of Dollars 40m, or 8 cents a
share, compared with earnings of Dollars 734m, or Dollars 1.29 a share, in
the same period of 1992. With the restructuring charge its net loss came to
Dollars 8bn.
The company said that when fully implemented, the restructuring would save
it Dollars 4bn a year.
The job cuts - roughly one fifth of IBM's workforce - and restructuring
charges were considerably larger than Wall Street had expected, but the
operating losses were smaller than most projections. IBM's shares rose
Dollars 3 1/4 on the New York Stock Exchange to Dollars 45 5/8 in late
trading.
Yesterday's cuts are the largest yet by IBM, which has been cutting staff
for years as it struggles with computer market changes favouring smaller,
nimbler rivals.
Mr Gerstner, whose strategy to restore IBM's fortunes has been the subject
of intense speculation, said his highest near-term priority was 'getting
IBM's cost and expense structure in line with the revenue realities of our
industry.'
His second priority was to 'win the battle in the customer's premises.' This
involved making IBM equipment easier to use and more able to link up with
non-proprietary computer systems.
He was also concerned to boost the morale of employees. However, he warned
that yesterday's cuts were based on current estimates of future demand and
further action could be necessary.
IBM announced at the start of 1993 that it expected to cut its staff of
around 300,000 by another 25,000 this year through voluntary and forced
redundancies.
Yesterday, it said that another 25,000 had now left or were committed to
leave by the end of the year and that some Dollars 2bn of the special charge
covered this rise in numbers.
A further 35,000 jobs would be cut by the end of 1994, requiring some
Dollars 4bn in charges.
Mr Gerstner said the job cuts would be more heavily weighted towards IBM's
operations outside the US.
The remaining Dollars 2.9bn of charges will cover cuts in manufacturing
capacity, office space and related expenses.
Andrew Adonis writes: IBM shed about 2,000 UK employees this year under a
voluntary separation programme which has now ended. Mr Peter Cruttenden,
IBM's UK finance director, said he did not expect further job cuts in the
UK.
Lex, Page 18
IBM aims to save Dollars 4bn, Page 24
World stocks, page 38
</TEXT>
