<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow climbs to new record on
economic data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US STOCK markets moved into record territory yesterday as investors opened
the week with a burst of buying, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed 20.96 higher at 3,567.70, its second
all-time peak in the past week. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 gained 1.99 at
449.09 and the Nasdaq composite 4.30 at 704.54. NYSE volume came to 224m
shares.
Stock prices opened firmer in the wake of strong overseas equity markets and
an early decline in bond yields. The overseas strength came from Europe,
where the main index of German stocks rose 1.3 per cent. In the US bond
market, prices advanced at the start of trading, pushing the yield below 6.7
per cent.
Although bonds later fluctuated between gains and losses, equities remained
higher throughout the day. Stocks were aided by some good economic news in
the form of a 1.9 per cent rise in June existing home sales. By mid-morning
the Dow had broken through its previous record of 3,555.40, set just last
week, and was showing a 20-point gain.
Prices eased back later in the morning as analysts voiced concern that the
markets would struggle to hold their new record levels. In recent weeks,
every time stocks have reached new highs, selling has quickly dragged prices
lower, and analysts fear a similar pattern could be repeated this week.
Stocks ended strongly, however, following a recovery in bond prices.
Among individual stocks, second-quarter earnings reports continued to
dominate. Boeing put on Dollars  7/8 at Dollars 38 5/8 in heavy trading
after the aircraft manufacturer posted stronger than expected earnings of
Dollars 426m. Investors shrugged off warnings from the company about its
near-term business prospects.
IBM initially traded lower ahead of today's expected unveiling of its
second-quarter results, but ended the day up Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 42 3/8
in volume of 3.9m shares. Analysts and investors continued to speculate that
the troubled computer group will announce a fresh charge against earnings,
further job cuts, and possibly a reduced dividend payout.
Cummins Engine, the world's biggest independent manufacturer of diesel
engines, tumbled Dollars 6 1/2 to Dollars 82 1/2 on news of lower than
expected second-quarter earnings.
Mobil firmed Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 72 3/8 after broking house Dean Witter
raised its 1993 earnings estimate for the oil company following its strong
second-quarter results.
On the Nasdaq market, Reuters ADRs climbed Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 65 after
the UK-based financial information group announced plans to buy back up to
5.8 per cent of its shares.
US Healthcare advanced Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 52 following an improvement
in second-quarter profits to 62 cents a share, up from 43 cents a year ago.
Canada
TORONTO ended a three-day losing streak, moving sharply higher in step with
other major world markets. The TSE 300 index surged 39.3 to 3,869.5 and
rises led falls by 407 to 289 after volume of 37.8m shares valued at
CDollars 414.9m. The golds group jumped 4.2 per cent as the New York bullion
price climbed USDollars 3.70 an ounce.
</TEXT>
