<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / Money Markets: French rates high
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MONEY market interest rates throughout Europe remained on the high side
yesterday at the start of another critical week inside the European exchange
rate mechanism, writes James Blitz.
Pressure on the French franc subsided as dealers waited to see how the
Bundesbank would respond to the latest crisis in the exchange rate mechanism
at its council meeting on Thursday.
French money market interest rates were more or less unchanged at 9.5 per
cent. But dealers in the interest rate futures market were looking for more
than 2 percentage points off three-month French francs by the middle of
September, with the September Pibor contract closing yesterday at 92.67.
The clear belief is that France will reduce interest rates either because
the Bundesbank has done so or because the French currency has quit the ERM.
There was speculation that the Bundesbank would reduce interest rates at
Thursday's council meeting, but there were wide differences of opin-ion over
the extent of the cut.
Some dealers felt that the Bundesbank would have to lower the discount rate
by a full percentage point to take pressure off the French currency. But the
price of interest rate futures appeared to imply that a 50 basis-point cut
was in the offing.
In recent days, the September Euromark contract has gradually risen from
93.20 to a close of 93.40 last night. This implies that three-month D-Marks
would be at 6.60 per cent by mid-September - and that would imply a
reduction in the German discount rate, currently at 6.75 per cent, of at
least 50 basis points.
Sterling interest rate markets were affected by the currency crisis
yesterday, with dealers speculating that German rate cuts might allow the UK
to ease policy.
In the middle of last week, the December short sterling contract hovered
around the 94.20 level. Yesterday it closed at 94.39, up 6 basis points on
the day. Some dealers believe that there could be  1/2 percentage point cut
in UK base rates later this year.
However, three-month sterling cash was virtually unchanged on the day at 6
per cent. Most of a Pounds 1.65bn shortage forecast by the Bank of England
was removed in the early round of discount market trading.
</TEXT>
