<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / International Company News: Novell warns of unchanged
earnings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NOVELL, the computer software company, yesterday announced that
third-quarter European sales were weaker than it had anticipated. It now
expected its earnings per share for the period to be flat relative to 1992.
The announcement came after the close of the New York Stock Exchange, where
Novell's shares had already fallen sharply yesterday as analysts anticipated
weaker-than-expected results. Novell closed at Dollars 21 1/4 , down Dollars
3 1/2 .
Analysts had previously expected earnings per share of around 27 cents, but
some cut these forecasts to around 23 cents yesterday. In the third quarter
of last year the company made 21 cents.
Novell, which is based in Utah and specialises in software to link computers
in local area networks, recently acquired Unix System Laboratories from
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph.
It said yesterday that because of the European weakness it now expected
total third-quarter revenue, including about Dollars 8m from Unix System
Laboratories, to be roughly flat with its second quarter. Net income per
share, exclusive of charges due to acquisitions, was now expected to decline
modestly from the previous quarter.
Revenues were expected to be up 15 per cent compared with the same quarter
of 1992. The company expects to announce its third-quarter figures during
the week of August 23.
</TEXT>
