<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / International Company News: Deutsche Bank joins rescue
effort for dairy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DEUTSCHE Bank, the agricultural ministry of Saxony and Sudmilch of Stuttgart
will try to arrange a rescue package for Sachsenmilch, the one eastern
German company listed on the Frankfurt stock exchange.
Sachsenmilch, a Saxon-based dairy, is part of the Sudmilch group. Deutsche
Bank, which helped it go public in 1991, had the shares suspended after
disclosures of over-spending.
Deutsche Bank, the company's principal creditor, says it was not told about
cost overruns by Sachsenmilch's former management.
'The facts were withheld from us. . . . .If we had known, we would have had
thought twice about going public,' the bank said.
The shares, floated at DM80, were suspended at DM60.
</TEXT>
