<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / Boeing shares rise despite warning on lower sales trend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BOEING, the world's largest commercial aircraft manufacturer, yesterday
reported a slight drop in second quarter net income and warned that a trend
towards lower sales would continue into 1994, because of a global economic
slowdown.
However, Boeing shares rose sharply on the New York Stock Exchange, closing
at Dollars 38 5/8 , up Dollars  7/8 , because the results were ahead of
analysts' expectations.
The company reported net earnings of Dollars 426m (Pounds 283m), or Dollars
1.25 a share, on sales of Dollars 7.98bn for the second quarter, compared
with Dollars 432m, or Dollars 1.27 a share, on sales of Dollars 7.8bn in the
same period last year. Analysts had expected earnings per share of around
Dollars 1.05.
Mr Frank Shrontz, chairman, said second-quarter sales were higher than the
first quarter's Dollars 6.6bn because of the timing of commercial jet
deliveries.
In the first six months Boeing earned Dollars 751m, or Dollars 2.21 a share,
down from the Dollars 852m, or Dollars 2.50 a share exclusive of accounting
adjustments, in the same period of 1992. Sales fell from Dollars 15.79bn to
Dollars 14.63bn.
The drop in first-half earnings resulted largely from lower sales in its
commercial aircraft and defence and space businesses. Boeing delivered 202
commercial aircraft in the period, down from 243 in the first half of 1992.
Defence and space sales were around 14 per cent lower.
Mr Shrontz said Boeing continued to expect full-year sales of around Dollars
26bn, down from Dollars 30.2bn in 1992. Second-half sales would be about 20
per cent lower than the first half, and this was consistent with cuts in
production already announced by the company.
'Based on current programmes and schedules, the trend of lower sales levels
will continue through 1994,' said Mr Shrontz.
'New orders for commercial transports continue to be below current delivery
rates, and some customer requests to reschedule existing orders continue to
be negotiated.'
However, the company said operating profit margins on commercial jets were
expected to be 'substantially maintained' as Boeing moved into this period
of lower production. Margins also continued to improve in the defence and
space business.
</TEXT>
