<TEXT>
Sir, The terms of the new International Cocoa Agreement ('Cocoa pact goes
for output management', July 20) should be most instructive to the
negotiation of the International Tropical Timber Agreement (ITTA). The cocoa
agreement rightly puts the emphasis on production management, whereas ITTA
negotiators still discuss, among other aspects, the suitability of a
reference to 'Target 2000', according to which all tropical timber reaching
international markets should be 'sustainably produced' by that date. Instead
of discussing time targets, ITTA negotiators would be better off to
concentrate on production management.
This would be most suitable to the ITTA, as it would lead to better prices
for tropical timber producers and a more environmentally friendly
exploitation of the tropical rain forest.
Environmental and economic objectives would be simultaneously addressed, and
the international tropical timber trade would stand a chance of subsisting
in the long run.
