<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Maastricht challenge opens in High
Court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD Rees-Mogg's attempt to block ratification of the Maastricht treaty was
launched in the High Court yesterday.
The former editor of The Times was in court to hear his counsel, Mr David
Pannick QC, accuse the government of acting unlawfully by seeking to ratify
the treaty without parliamentary approval.
Mr Pannick moved to reassure the court that the case did not pose a threat
to the rights and privileges of the Houses of Parliament. Last week Miss
Betty Boothroyd, the Speaker of the Commons, warned the courts not to
interfere in parliamentary proceedings.
Mr Pannick said: 'These proceedings in our submission do not involve any
questioning of proceedings in the Houses of Parliament contrary to article
nine of the Bill of Rights 1688.'
He told a packed courtroom that the case was not concerned with the merits
of the UK's decision to sign the treaty nor with the wisdom - or folly - of
the UK's intention to ratify it. The proceedings were solely concerned with
the legality of the government's proposed course of action.
The essence of the case was that 'contrary to the requirements laid down by
parliament itself in the 1972 European Communities Act and the 1978 European
Parliamentary Elections Act, the Crown, through the government, intends,
without the authorisation of parliament, to increase the powers of the
European parliament to alter the content of Community law'.
Mr Pannick said the government was acting unlawfully in three respects:
It intended to increase the powers of the European parliament by ratifying
the protocol on social policy.
Without parliamentary authority it intended to alter the content of the
Treaty of Rome by ratifying the protocol on social policy.
Without parliamentary authority it intended to ratify title V of the Treaty
on European Union which deals with a common foreign and security policy
which would transfer prerogative powers away from the UK.
Mr Sydney Kentridge QC for Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, said that
Lord Rees-Mogg's case was based on 'fundamental constitutional
misconceptions' and amounted to an attack on parliament.
Considered as a whole, he said he regarded 'with some scepticism' Mr
Pannick's disclaimer that the challenge had nothing to do with the merits or
demerits of the decision to ratify the treaty.
Rejecting Lord Rees-Mogg's assertion that his aim was not to interfere with
political debate in parliament, Mr Kentridge suggested that 'sometimes
judicial review may be the continuation of politics by other means'.
He said: 'We were told that the government's decision was an attempt by the
Crown to reassert powers which had been lost to them at the end of the 17th
century. 'We submit it is nothing of the sort. There is no conflict at all
between the Crown and Parliament.'
The hearing is expected to last until tomorrow.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
