<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Tory hopes fade over by-election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TORIES seem to have all but thrown in the towel for the Christchurch
by-election as their campaign moves falteringly into the final days.
None of the party's crowd-pullers is scheduled to appear in a last-ditch
effort to persuade traditional supporters in the south coast constituency to
turn back to the Tories.
Mr William Waldegrave, the public services minister, is due in Christchurch
this morning but tomorrow the Tories' campaign will be left to Sir Norman
Fowler, the party chairman, making his customary eve-of-poll appearance.
The arrangements for rallies by the three main parties last night added to
the impression that the Tories have no real hope for the seat. The Liberal
Democrats, who are tipped to score a resounding victory, fielded Mr Paddy
Ashdown, the party leader; Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, turned
out for Labour, while Sir Edward Heath, the former prime minister, spoke at
the Tories' public meeting.
Sir Edward has recently fuelled the row over Europe within the Conservative
party by outspoken attacks on the Euro-sceptics, and it appears to have been
the local constituency association, rather than central office, that thought
it would be helpful to make use of his offer to assist the campaign.
Both the Tories and the Liberal Democrats were, however, playing down
constituency opinion polls which suggested that the Tory majority of 23,000
would be convincingly overturned.
Mrs Diana Maddock, the Liberal Democrat, thought it was 'doubtful' that the
current state of opinion was as good for her party as the polls suggested.
There were, she said, still 'an awful lot of Conservatives' who were
undecided.
Labour yesterday claimed that the Liberal Democrats were home and dry, and
so Labour supporters did not have to vote tactically to ensure the
Conservatives lost.
Mr Robert Hayward, the Tory candidate, said one-off constituency polls were
inaccurate.
'There are a large number of waverers and we are targeting them to achieve
victory on Thursday,' he said.
</TEXT>
