<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Wealthy backers share high cost of
going to law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM KING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUDICIAL REVIEW of the Maastricht treaty's ratification does not come cheap.
Lord Rees-Mogg has been able to bring his application to the High Court only
because he has financial backing from wealthy opponents of the treaty,
particularly Sir James Goldsmith.
This week's High Court hearing will cost tens of thousands of pounds a day,
with the final cost of the case multiplying if, as expected, it goes on to
the Court of Appeal.
Mr Jeremy Nieboer, a senior partner at solicitors Gouldens which is handling
the case, said a limit had been set for the cost of the case.
Lord Rees-Mogg's case was put by Mr David Pannick QC, yesterday, supported
by three other barristers. Normal charges for top barristers taking the
brief would suggest fees of Pounds 25,000, with further charges amounting to
Pounds 3,750 for each day of the hearing.
Putting the case for the Foreign and Commonwealth Office is Mr Sydney
Kentridge QC, supported by three other barristers. This is likely to cost a
further Pounds 25,000 in brief fees and Pounds 3,500 a day to appear at
court.
Lord Rees-Mogg might have to pay the Foreign Office's costs if he loses the
case.
Three other eminent - and expensive - barristers have been involved in
preparation of the case: Mr Leolin Price QC, who represented Lord Rees-Mogg
at the first application for judicial review, Mr John McDonnell QC and Sir
Patrick Neill QC, warden of All Souls, whom the anti-Maastricht camp had
originally hoped to make their lead counsel for the hearing.
Mr Jeremy Nieboer said he had become involved in the case in February and it
had taken up most of his time since June.
The services of a leading solicitor costs upwards of Pounds 180 an hour, so
the practice account could total tens of thousands of pounds.
</TEXT>
