<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Minister rejects claims of regional
aid 'bribes'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR TIM SAINSBURY, industry minister, yesterday rejected Labour allegations
that political gerrymandering had determined changes in the areas qualifying
for regional aid.
He told the Commons the new assisted areas map announced on Friday ensured
that help would be concentrated on areas with the most problems. Mr
Sainsbury said that the changes made to the previous map drawn up in 1984
reflected the fact that unemployment had fallen in the north and north-west
while it had risen in London, the south-east and south-west.
Mr Neil Kinnock, the former Labour leader, accused the government of
indulging in 'pork-barrel politics' and Mr Bob Cryer (Lab Bradford South)
said that the new map reflected attempts to 'bribe' Tory MPs opposed to the
Maastricht treaty.
Mr Gerald Kaufman (Lab Manchester Gorton) complained that his constituency
would get 'no help at all' while Sutton Coldfield, represented by Sir Norman
Fowler, the Conservative party chairman, with less unemployment, was among
the beneficiaries.
Sir Teddy Taylor (C Southend East), a leading opponent of the Maastricht
treaty, protested that a decision by the European Commission had resulted in
Southend being excluded at what Mr Paul Channon (C Southend West) described
as 'the very last minute'.
Mr Sainsbury confirmed the commission had cut the overall coverage of
assisted area status, but stressed that the UK had not suffered as much as
Germany, which had been subjected to a 2 per cent reduction.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, said that aid was being
provided for new areas by taking away help from other areas which still
needed support.
</TEXT>
