<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / M&amp;S offers graduates 1-year jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MARKS and Spencer, the clothes and food retailing chain, is to employ 100
graduates on one-year contracts because of 'concern about graduate
unemployment'.
The temporary contract jobs are in addition to the company's normal graduate
intake.
M and S said the scheme was being sponsored by Sir Richard Greenbury,
chairman of the company. Sir Richard said the special programme 'will enable
an additional 100 graduates to benefit from our one-year training programme
even though we are unable to guarantee a full career'.
The move follows a recent report from members of the Association of Graduate
Recruiters, of which M and S is a leading member, which said employers were
forecasting a fall of 6.5 per cent in vacancies for graduates this year,
compared with last year.
Since the forecast there have been reports of a late surge in interest by
employers in taking on extra graduate recruits.
Details of the M and S scheme were disclosed yesterday by Personnel Today
magazine.
The temporary recruits will take part in the training programme for
permanent graduate recruits and will be paid the same annual salary of
Pounds 14,000. They will receive career counselling to help them find
alternative employment at the end of their year with the company.
Ms Michelle Mendelsson, M and S recruitment manager, said that if the
company saw outstanding performers among the 100 temporary recruits it would
make permanent jobs available. The scheme was 'absolutely not' a way of
identifying high-flyers and eliminating less able trainees without any
further commitment, she said.
M and S said it believed it was the first company to provide a temporary
work scheme of this nature to graduates. Those who took part in it would
'have the benefit of being able to list work experience with M and S on
their CV,' it said.
The company announced recently that it would be taking an extra 100
graduates into permanent employment. It originally decided to take 150
graduates.
It said one of the reasons for raising its graduate intake to 250 was
because of the declining number of A-level entrants. More sixth-formers have
been continuing their education rather than seeking jobs.
In 1991 M and S froze graduate appointments after having offered jobs to 100
candidates - 70 went on to join the company last year.
</TEXT>
