<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / London's tax burden criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDONERS AND those working in London pay Pounds 8bn a year more in taxes
than is spent by central and local government in the capital, according to a
report to be published on Friday by the Corporation of London, the local
authority for the City of London.
The report, by Professor Douglas McWilliams of the Centre for Economics and
Business Research, says that the transfer of resources out of London on such
a scale will reduce the rate of growth in the UK economy.
The findings will provide further ammunition for businesses and London
pressure groups campaigning for more of the taxes paid in London to be
ploughed back into the capital's economy through an increase in public
investment in transport infrastructure.
The report says that investment in transport projects such as the
modernisation of the London Underground would increase GDP more than if the
same amounts were spent on social and other programmes elsewhere in the UK.
All countries have parts that are more prosperous than others and make a net
contribution to public finances, the report says. The contribution made by
London is unusually large, however. By adding to business costs it will
damage London's economic prospects in competing with other European cities
as a financial centre. That, it is argued, will reduce the rate of growth in
the rest of the economy, which is heavily reliant on London's prosperity.
The report says nearly 3m jobs outside London depend wholly or partly on
supplying the capital.
The report says that if greater London were an independent state its GDP
would be more than Pounds 70bn - larger than four EC member states and
comparable with that of Hong Kong. It would also have a healthy trade
surplus. Exports of goods and services to the rest of the UK and the world
exceeded imports by Pounds 10.6bn in 1989.
'In broad terms, London's economy is based on services, a high proportion of
which is exported,' said Prof McWilliams. 'It largely consumes manufactured
goods, a high proportion of which is imported.'
The fact that taxes paid have exceeded public expenditure in the capital for
decades is partly because people working in London have higher earnings. The
average job in London generates 43 per cent more income-based tax than the
average job in the UK.
Current public spending in London in relation to GDP is only 74 per cent of
the national average, however. Prof McWilliams says this is because much of
public spending goes on social support and relatively little on supporting
business. The report says: 'Without the London contribution, the UK public
sector borrowing requirement would be 10.6 per cent of non-London GDP -
higher than any other OECD country other than Italy.'
London's Contribution to the UK Economy. PR Office, Corporation of London,
Guildhall, London EC2P 2EJ. Free.
 ---------------------------------------------------
                   LONDON'S GDP
           some international comparisons
 ---------------------------------------------------
                          GDP         Pop
                       Dollars bn     (m)
 ---------------------------------------------------
United Kingdom            937        57.9
Sweden                    260         8.7
Belgium                   225        10.0
Denmark                   145         5.2
Russia                    125       149.0
Greater London            122         6.8
Saudi Arabia              122        16.4
Hong Kong                 111         5.9
Portugal                   80        10.5
Singapore                  52         2.8
Ireland                    50         3.7
 ---------------------------------------------------
Source: Centre for Economics and Business Research
