<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / Whitehall property agencies reviewed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CABINET office has launched a review into the efficiency with which the
Civil Service manages government property holdings.
The review will look at the scope for giving departments and agencies
greater responsibility for managing their property, including acquisition
and disposal.
Sir Peter Levene, the prime minister's efficiency adviser, will carry out
the review, which covers thousands of properties across the UK.
The largest organisation managing government property is Property Holdings,
part of the Department of the Environment, which manages contracts worth
Pounds 2bn a year.
With more than 3,000 properties under management it is responsible for 60
per cent of the government's civil estate, housing parts of more than 50
departments and public bodies.
The terms of reference of the review indicate that the government is
concerned that it should not lose benefits that centralised arrangements
offer in the property market. Arrangements to avoid competition between
departments will be considered.
The review will also examine whether central advice will be needed on
matters such as health and safety, fire precautions and environmental
issues. It is due to be completed by the end of the year.
</TEXT>
