FT  27 JUL 93 / Private medicine report delayed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MONOPOLIES and Mergers Commission was yesterday given an extra three
months - until December 7 - to complete a report into private medical
services.
Private medical fees were referred to the commission last September.
In a letter to doctors earlier this month the commission said it believed
that the way some National Health Service consultants set private fees close
to the guidelines of the British Medical Association and private health
insurers formed a complex monopoly under the Fair Trading Act.
But the commission stressed that it had not reached final conclusions, or
decided whether the effects of the conduct were good or bad.
A challenge to the wool-buying monopoly of the British Wool Marketing Board
failed yesterday when the Court of Session in Edinburgh banned wool
merchants Reid and Robertson from attempting to buy wool direct from
farmers.
Mr John King, the company's director, said the company would continue
lobbying parliament for a change in the law on wool marketing.
Reid and Robertson had told the court that since the government's removal of
the wool price guarantee farmers were still obliged to sell wool to the
board, but at a reduced price.
