Mr Clarke's disclosure to the employment select committee raises questions
about whether British Coal will be able to match last year's operating
profits for both deep mine and opencast operations of Pounds 545m, an
improvement of Pounds 123m on the previous year.
Although it made an operating profit in 1992-93, exceptional costs of Pounds
1.02bn turned this into an overall loss of Pounds 588m, British Coal said
last week when it announced its full-year results.
British Coal is struggling with a substantial fall both in sales and in
prices. The electricity generators are taking just 40m tonnes of coal this
year compared with 65m last year, and at prices at least 15 per cent lower.
Mr Clarke said after the committee meeting that in spite of the losses the
mines were operating ahead of budget. He indicated that results would
