<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / Banks predict crackdown on 'laundering'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CLEARING BANKS yesterday predicted a big rise in the number of transactions
reported to police as possible cases of criminal activity after an imminent
change in the law introduces the threat that employees who fail to do so may
be jailed.
The British Bankers' Association forecast a 'very significant' rise in the
20,000 cases of possible money laundering which are reported by bank
employees from the 1.6bn transactions that take place each year.
The Criminal Justice Bill, expected to receive royal assent this week, is
likely to lead to a sharp increase in the reporting requirements on banks
and other financial-services companies from April next year.
The bill widens the requirements so that banks must report not only
transactions suspected to be linked to money laundering and terrorism, but
also possible serious criminal activity such as fraud, theft and extortion.
It also introduces for the first time a penalty of up to five years'
imprisonment for bank employees who are negligent in reporting suspicious
activities, and up to two years' jail for directors of organisations that
are negligent.
Banks have argued successfully against the compulsory reporting of all
transactions above a certain size, as is the case in the US. Sir Nicholas
Goodison, association president, said this would have been 'crazy'.
But the banks have accepted additional costs - estimated at up to Pounds 30m
in the first year and Pounds 20m in subsequent years - associated with
additional staff training and the setting up of central reporting offices to
review branch suspicions.
Ms Sue Thornhill, the association's assistant director, said there was
likely to be 'an increase in suspicion at all levels' in banks as a result
of the introduction of the threat of criminal prosecution for negligent
staff and managers.
The association also emphasised its support for the call by Mr Eric Howe,
data protection registrar, for a tightening of the law to prevent people who
manage to obtain confidential data from banks from selling it to third
parties.
Lord Inchyra, director-general of the association, said that there appeared
to be 'a hole' in the law because it was not an offence to trade in
information, including account details, that was held as confidential data.
He said the association had developed guidance notes for banks to tighten
their security.
</TEXT>
