<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / Treasury toes production line: Peter Marsh weighs the
criticism of an initiative that gives senior civil servants a taste of
industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR DOUGLAS Wass, Treasury permanent secretary between 1974 and 1983 and the
person who has served longest in the post since the 1950s, likes to tell
acquaintances how he would have done his job better if he had had more
insights into the business world.
In the past few months Britain's most powerful government department has
been trying to transplant knowledge of industry into the minds of its top
officials, most of whom have never worked outside the Civil Service. The top
100 civil servants have been ordered to visit an industrial site at least
once a year.
The Treasury has also set up a new 'supply side' unit which will try to
ensure that more of its officials think about manufacturing issues. It aims
to do this while at the same time fulfilling its two main functions of
controlling public spending and co-ordinating macroeconomic policies in
pursuit of low inflation.
While some see the moves as practical steps to introduce new thinking into
the department, others believe they are aimed at deflecting criticism away
from the Treasury and keeping pace in the Whitehall pecking-order with a
resurgent Department of Trade and Industry.
The drive has been given new emphasis by the appointment as chancellor of Mr
Kenneth Clarke, who has stressed a new commitment to helping wealth
creation. It was set in train last year by Sir Terry Burns, permanent
secretary at the Treasury since 1991 and the government's chief economic
adviser before that.
Many have identified Sir Terry as having presided over a series of mistakes
in economic policymaking. In particular he is said not to have paid enough
attention to the role of manufacturing, to have underestimated the
inflationary boom of the late 1980s and to have misjudged the seriousness of
the recession.
The new programme is described by Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary at
the Treasury, as a effort to create a 'friendly environment' for business in
the department.
The Treasury's 'supply-side' unit is in its industry division and headed by
Mr Bill Guy, a long-serving Treasury official. Mr Guy will have just one
other colleague in his unit, an economist. Although Mr Dorrell concedes that
two people on supply-side policies does not sound very much, 'it's more than
we've had before'.
Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the Confederation of British Industry,
criticises the Treasury for its past attitudes to business. Even so, he
finds the new initiatives encouraging.
He said: 'You will see quite an impact (in government policies) if the
Treasury begins to build up its own contacts with industry and gain a better
understanding of what business does. What we are seeing is a shift in the
balance of government policy a little more towards industry.'
Mr Graham Mather, president of the European Policy Forum, an independent
think-tank, is more sceptical. 'In part the effort is an understandable
self-defence against the threat of a rejuvenated Department of Trade and
Industry which is stepping up its own contacts with business. The programme
also represents belated recognition by officials that they need to correct
the impression of having underperformed during the 1980s.'
One former senior official at the Treasury, who left in the past five years,
says better contacts with industry might be a useful step but should go
further than short factory visits. The former official said: 'If the
Treasury really wants to understand industry it should go to the trouble of
fixing up discussions with specialised people such as finance directors,
whose pre-occupations are similar to those at the Treasury but who offer a
private-sector view. I don't see that spending a few hours watching widgets
bashed out will help very much.'
In spite of these comments, one of the businessmen on the receiving end of a
Treasury visit a few weeks ago thought it a useful exercise. Mr Paul Farrow,
managing director of West Midlands engineering company Deritend Precision
Castings, said of the half-day he spent with his Treasury guest: 'The
Treasury guy listened and at the end of his day with us understood some of
our problems. In the past, Treasury officials have lacked understanding
about industry because they've so little experience of it.'
Mr David Smith, managing director of Nesbit Evans, a maker of hospital beds,
also in the West Midlands, is similarly pleased about the visit two Treasury
officials made to his company recently.
He said he told the Treasury pair how the National Health Service could save
'tens of millions of pounds a year' by ordering his own variety of
power-assisted, washable hospital beds rather than the less sophisticated
types currently purchased.
He insisted this was not an example of 'special pleading' aimed at
increasing his factory's orders, but a straightforward case of exchanging
information in a way which - if his ideas are acted on - could cut Britain's
soaring public borrowing.
The Treasury has also been making greater efforts to talk to Mr Neil
Johnson, director-general of the Engineering Employers' Federation.
Mr Johnson is pleased by Mr Clarke's declaration of greater interest in
manufacturing. However, he still thinks the Treasury is too much weighed
down by its public-spending remit.
'I'm encouraged by the progress so far,' Mr Johnson said, 'but the Treasury
needs to go further in moving from a negative, counting-house mentality
towards a style which fits in with the real world.'
</TEXT>
