<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / Company probes by DTI up 50%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER OF confidential company investigations started and completed by
the Department of Trade and Industry's investigation division rose by more
than 50 per cent in the first quarter of this year, figures released
yesterday show.
Sixty-three investigations were started and 64 were completed, compared with
40 started and 35 completed in the previous quarter. The division looks into
insider dealing and other offences under companies, financial services and
insolvency legislation.
Complaints and requests for company investigations to the DTI rose by more
than 20 per cent, from 280 in the previous quarter to 338.
Three people were convicted during the quarter following prosecutions
resulting from investigations carried out in earlier periods. In one case
two defendants pleaded guilty to false accounting offences and were
sentenced to 15 months and nine months imprisonment respectively, both
suspended for two years.
A defendant found guilty of fraudulent trading, theft, and possession of
forged share certificates was sentenced to 2 1/2 years imprisonment and
disqualified from acting as a company director for five years.
