FT  27 JUL 93 / Protest held at printing plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A MASS demonstration was held outside the Bristol printing plant of JW
Arrowsmith yesterday to mark three months since the dismissal of most of its
workforce, Roland Adburgham writes. Police estimated that about 450 people
took part.
The company, which specialises in printing technical journals, sacked 120
printers after they took industrial action over a pay claim. They were
offered reinstatement at their previous pay levels but were told the company
would no longer recognise their union, the Graphical, Paper &amp; Media Union.
The plant has since been picketed and on July 9 the company obtained a High
Court injunction against the union, restricting the number of pickets to
six. The area branch of the GPMU said yesterday that its officials had not
taken part in the demonstration outside the works but had held a separate
meeting in the city centre.
JW Arrowsmith has been advertising jobs to replace the sacked workers. Miss
Victoria Arrowsmith-Brown, chairman and managing director, said staff were
being hired at the rate of one or two a week.
