<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / Inflation in Germany edges higher
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INCREASES in insurance costs and dearer bananas contributed to a further
increase in western German inflation this month.
Provisional figures from three main states, published yesterday, tended to
confirm forecasts of a modest rise in the cost-of-living index.
Most economists expect an annual rate of between 4.2 per cent and 4.4 per
cent for all of western Germany to be ann-ounced later this week when the
various state figures have been collated. Figures for June showed an annual
inflation rate of 4.2 per cent.
Early in the day, the stock market received a boost when Baden-Wurttemberg
reported a rise of just 0.1 per cent in consumer prices over June. Traders
speculated this might encourage the Bundesbank to cut interest rates on
Thursday.
But later details, showing price increases of 0.2 per cent on the month in
North Rhine-Westphalia and Hesse, raising annual inflation rates there to
4.1 per cent and 4.8 per cent respectively, were more in line with general
forecasts.
Economists suggested that the figures had already been allowed for in the
Bundesbank's calculations and that the main question was how far the central
bank felt able to move to support the French franc without compromising its
reputation for firm resistance to inflation.
Ms Ros Lifton at Nomura Research in Frankfurt found the decision 'hard to
call', although a further 'encouraging' cut in the rate at which the central
bank supplies wholesale funds to the market was possible. This 'repo' rate
was set last week at 7.15 per cent, and any further cuts will be made known
tomorrow.
Deutsche Bank Research suggested there was a 60 per cent chance of a cut in
the Bundesbank's key discount rate on Thursday. Deutsche Bank's Paris office
said an 'unambiguous' reduction would take the pressure off the franc,
although most observers believe the Bundesbank is more likely to continue
its quarter or half-point cuts.
High rents and service costs are still the main source of inflationary
pressure, but an increase in taxes on insurance premiums, introduced on July
1, have also played a role.
In North Rhine-Westphalia, statisticians noted that bananas, Germany's most
popular fruit, are 30 per cent dearer than a year ago because the EC has
forced Germany to buy from dearer suppliers.
</TEXT>
