<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / News Corp in Dollars 525m deal for Hong Kong TV group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY and SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, GUANGDONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR RUPERT MURDOCH's News Corporation yesterday bought control of
HutchVision, operator of StarTV, a Hong Kong-based satellite television
system whose broadcasts reach 38 countries from China and Indonesia to Japan
and Afghanistan.
The Dollars 525m (Pounds 350m) deal takes Mr Murdoch a large step towards
realising his media ambitions in Asia. Star TV's five channels, including
BBC World Service Television, are available to an estimated 45m viewers in
11m homes.
Half the consideration for the deal, which values Star at Dollars 850m, is
in cash and the other half in News Corp shares.
Mr Murdoch said last night: 'I am very, very thrilled. It's got a long way
to go but it has got the potential to be two or three Skys.'
News Corp has a 50 per cent stake in British Sky Broadcasting, which runs
Sky Television in the UK, a venture in which Pearson, owner of the Financial
Times, also has a stake.
Mr Murdoch beat Pearson, the media and banking group, to take a 63.6 per
cent stake in the Hong Kong broadcaster. Some Pearson executives apparently
thought until recently that the deal was theirs. Pearson was not available
for comment last night.
Mr Murdoch signed the HutchVision agreement last Thursday on his yacht
Morning Glory in the Mediterranean with Mr Li Ka-shing, one of the richest
men in Hong Kong. Mr Li and his family own 50 per cent of HutchVision. The
rest is owned by Hutchison Whampoa, a company which Mr Li controls.
A Hong Kong executive close to the negotiations said last night: 'I don't
think that Julian Mounter (chief executive of Star) is a very happy man.
He's not sure if it is Christmas or Easter. He was dealing with Pearson.'
Pearson is believed to have offered considerably more than News Corp for the
Star stake. A key factor in the deal may have been an undertaking by Mr
Murdoch to have a public issue of HutchVision shares so Mr Li could sell his
remaining stake if he wished. It was also clear that News Corp would have
found a way of competing against Star if it had failed to buy control.
Hutchison and the Li family will retain 36.4 per cent of the venture and
will remain in control of the company that holds the operating licence from
the Kong Kong government.
This means that unlike Mr Murdoch's Dollars 238.8m bid last month for a 22
per cent stake in Television Broadcasts (TVB), a domestic television company
in Hong Kong, no regulatory issues on ownership are involved.
The TVB deal was withdrawn for consideration in the face of opposition,
partly because Mr Murdoch already owns the highly profitable South China
Morning Post but is still not being ruled out formally by News Corp despite
yesterday's acquisition.
Hutchison and the Li family said the transaction represented six times the
funds which the partners had invested in the satellite venture. This
excludes the money put into Media Assets, a separate company set up to buy
programme rights. Media Assets will now be acquired at cost by HutchVision
for Dollars 64m. Hutchison said it had made an extraordinary gain of
HKDollars 1.5bn (Pounds 129.3m).
Mr Murdoch who has been targeting the Asian television market for some time
made a bid, worth an estimated Dollars 250m, for control of Star some months
ago that was rejected. Although he then made his move on TVB, which has
linked up with Turner Broadcasting and other American broadcasters to
transmit a service on an Indonesian satellite, many believe Star was always
the target.
Star plans to launch a pay television package of channels in October.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
