<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUL 93 / Reuters to spend Pounds 350m of cash pile on share buy-back
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REUTERS, the international news and information group, is to spend up to
Pounds 350m buying back its own shares in the largest repurchase operation
by a British company since the mid-1980s. News of the plan, under which
Reuters would take back 5.8 per cent of its equity, sent the shares up 36p
to Pounds 14.40.
Reuters, which had planned to unveil the scheme today with its interim
results, said it had been obliged to bring forward the announcement by press
speculation.
Shareholders will receive Pounds 14 a share, but tax credits will make it
worth as much as Pounds 17.25 to tax-exempt gross income funds. The tax
credits mean individual shareholders will receive Pounds 16.25, but that
will be subject to capital gains and income tax.
Reuters has been piling up cash over the last few years and had a balance of
Pounds 710m at its December year-end. It promised in March to consider ways
of returning cash to shareholders - either by a special dividend or share
buy-back. Sir Christopher Hogg, chairman, said: 'Whilst the main purpose of
the repurchase is to provide shareholders with the opportunity either to
receive a cash distribution or to have an equivalent enhancement of their
investment in Reuters, the board believes that all shareholders will benefit
from the repurchase since it should lead to an increase in Reuters' earnings
per share.'
In what Reuters described as a 'pioneering scheme', the 34 per cent of the
group's equity held as American Depositary Shares will also receive a UK tax
refund. The tax credit arises because the Inland Revenue views such cash
distributions as dividends, on which advance corporation tax is payable but
may be reclaimed.
All shareholders will be entitled to sell 5.8 per cent of their holding,
although they will be able to sell more, to the extent that other
shareholders do not take up their full entitlement.
Sir Christopher said: 'The difference between a special dividend and
buy-back are quite marked on closer examination. We like this scheme because
it gives shareholders a choice - they can either take the cash, or have an
enhanced stake in the company.'
Mr Peter Job, chief executive, said: 'We have absorbed two messages from
shareholders - they want us to continue to invest in the business, but they
don't want us to invest just for the sake of investing.'
Editorial Comment, Page 17
Lex, Page 18
