<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 93 / Economics: More bad news for France
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRIDAY WILL be an uncomfortable day for the French government with the
release of unemployment statistics for June. The expected rise in the rate
of unemployment to 11.6 per cent comes at a time when the government is
under pressure to ease monetary policy, but is prevented from doing so
because of its commitment to keeping the franc at its current value against
other European currencies.
Until Germany eases its interest rates, short of leaving the European
exchange rate mechanism, it appears that the French government will have to
preside over the unpopular combination of high unemployment and high real
interest rates.
There will be no easing of pressure on the UK government this week. Although
strong economic statistics are working in the government's favour - the
Confederation of British Industry's industrial trends survey tomorrow is
expected to confirm a steady economic recovery - the Conservative party
looks set to lose the Christchurch by-election on Thursday.
The following are some of the week's other economic highlights and events.
The figures in brackets are the median of economists' forecasts from MMS
International, a financial information company.
Today: UK, Franco-British summit: attended by Mitterand, Balladur and Major.
Germany, July cost of living for Badenwuertt and Hessen. US, June existing
home sales.
Tomorrow: UK, parliamentary recess begins; Q2 CBI quarterly industrial
trends survey. US, July consumer confidence (57.0); Johnson Redbook week
ended July 24. Japan, June retail sales (down 5.4 per cent on the year).
Australia, Reserve Bank of Australia board meeting.
Wednesday: US, June durable goods orders (up 1 per cent), durable shipments.
Canada, June industrial production price index (up 0.1 per cent on month),
raw materials price index (down 0.6 per cent on month). Australia, Q2
consumer prices index (up 0.5 per cent on quarter, up 2 per cent on year).
Thursday: UK, Christchurch by-election. Germany, Bundesbank council meeting
in Frankfurt. Summer recess follows with no more meetings until August 26.
US, advance figures for Q2 GDP (up 2.2 per cent), advance deflator (up 2.8
per cent); initial claims week ended July 24 (349,000); state benefits week
ended July 17; June export price index, import price index; money supply
data for week ended July 19. Canada, May employment earnings (up 2 per cent
on year). Japan, June industrial production (up 1.6 per cent), shipments.
Australia, June current account (ADollars 1.5bn deficit), building approvals
(up 4 per cent).
Friday: France, June unemployment rate (11.6 per cent). US, June new home
sales (614,000), personal income (up 0.1 per cent); July Chicago NAPM; July
Michigan sentiment; July agriculture prices; June bank credit. Canada, May
real GDP (up 0.1 per cent on month). Japan, July Tokyo CPI (up 1.4 per cent
on year), excluding perishables (up 1.4 per cent on year), national CPI (up
0.9 per cent on year), excluding perishables (up 1.1 per cent on year); June
unemployment rate, construction orders, construction starts, housing starts
(up 2.2 per cent on year).
During the week: Germany, June import prices (flat on month, down 3.2 per
cent on year); July cost of living for Bavaria and Nord-rhine Westphalia,
preliminary cost of living (up 0.1 per cent on month, up 4.3 per cent on
year). Italy, June M2 (up 6.1 per cent on year), bank lending (up 5 per cent
on year), trade balance (L1.5trillion surplus), balance of payments
(L1trillion surplus), foreign exchange reserves (L67trillion). Spain, Q2
unemployment rate (22.4 per cent); May industrial production (down 5 per
cent on year). Belgium, June CPI (up 2.6 per cent on year). Switzerland,
June Geneva CPI. Japan, LDP elects party president; July wholesale prices
index - second ten days.
</TEXT>
