<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 93 / International Company News: Shortfall at Quantum deepens in
quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
QUANTUM, the US chemicals group which has agreed a Dollars 3.2bn bid from
Hanson, the Anglo-American conglomerate, reported a second-quarter loss,
before income tax benefit, of Dollars 84.2m compared with a loss of Dollars
68.3m for the same quarter last year.
The results were worse than expected. Turnover fell from Dollars 542m to
Dollars 527m. Petrochemicals sales fell from Dollars 425m to Dollars 407m
and generated a trading loss of Dollars 5.5m compared with an operating
profit for the same quarter last year of Dollars 10.6m.
The group, the largest US manufacturer of polyethylene, said that sales of
the product were flat, and that average selling prices were lower than last
year, particularly for high density polyethylene.
The weak state of the European economies also affected volumes, selling
prices and profit margins for the group's other main products.
The company said margins were further weakened by the higher cost of
ethylene, the principle component for most plastics, and the temporary
closure of the group's ethylene facility in Morris, Illinois.
The propane operations, the second largest in the US, increased sales from
Dollars 117m to Dollars 120m. Operating profits were Dollars 2.2m compared
with a quarterly loss last year of Dollars 5.3m.
</TEXT>
